&lt;p&gt;Why do computer scientist create different programming languages?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Think about this: there are nearly 8,000 human languages spoken around the world. Some, like English or Mandarin, are spoken by millions. Others are known only to small communities tucked away in remote regions. But it’s not just about numbers—languages are shaped by culture, geography, and history. How a civilization farms, trades, worships, or governs—these things all influence how its language sounds and works. And as times change, so do languages. New needs bring new words, new grammar, even entirely new ways of speaking. Language evolves because people evolve.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
